03738nam a22005535i 9780822382065DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t19971997ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223820657 a10.1515/97808223820652doi  a(DE-B1597)553041  a(OCoLC)841913157  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aB2430.F724bR36 1997 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a3202201 aRansom, John S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFoucault's Discipline :bThe Politics of Subjectivity /cJohn S. Ransom. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Rethinking "Critique" -- tI Confronting New Forms of Power -- tII Disciplines and the Individual -- tIII Governmentality and Population -- tIV Genealogy in the Disciplinary Age -- tV The "Plebeian Aspect" -- tVI Politics, Norms, and the Self -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Foucault’s Discipline, John S. Ransom extracts a distinctive vision of the political world—and oppositional possibilities within it—from the welter of disparate topics and projects Michel Foucault pursued over his lifetime. Uniquely, Ransom presents Foucault as a political theorist in the tradition of Weber and Nietzsche, and specifically examines Foucault’s work in relation to the political tradition of liberalism and the Frankfurt School. By concentrating primarily on Discipline and Punish and the later Foucauldian texts, Ransom provides a fresh interpretation of this controversial philosopher’s perspectives on concepts such as freedom, right, truth, and power.Foucault’s Discipline demonstrates how Foucault’s valorization of descriptive critique over prescriptive plans of action can be applied to the decisively altered political landscape of the end of this millennium. By reconstructing the philosopher’s arguments concerning the significance of disciplinary institutions, biopower, subjectivity, and forms of resistance in modern society, Ransom shows how Foucault has provided a different way of looking at and responding to contemporary models of government—in short, a new depiction of the political world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aIntersubjectivity. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z97831107136020 cprintz978082231878140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822382065?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822382065423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822382065/original  a978-3-11-071360-2  Duke University Press Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles